<br>
Golden rays of sunlight illuminated High Castle as the sun began to sink below the distant line of the horizon. The chilling caress of Fall had left nothing untouched in this region. Small branches and leaves littered the pocked ground. Thin, half-barren trees no longer hid the furthest skyward reaching edifices of the proud and stalwart High Castle. <br>
<br>
Time seemed to stand still in a final moment of resistance as the light of day valiantly fought against the inevitable hordes of night. One last ray of hope flared briefly across the darkening sky in a desperate attempt to stay afloat, but shadows drowned the land and the glimmering hope flickered briefly and was gone. Darkness rode a swift horse across the plains of Karana and blanketed the land, covering the fortress’ façade. A heavy, oppressive darkness seeped into the tiny crevices between the brick and mortar. It crept under the cracks of doors and windows, and embraced the fortress as if it was an old, familiar friend. <br>
<br>
As darkness settled about High Castle and aged boards and wood creaked under the added weight, a slight wind began to stir, pushing dry leaves about like a small whirling dervish dancing fervently across the courtyard. The fires lighting the torches and sconces moved in synchronous rhythm, swaying to an unheard beat known only to the wind. <br>
<br>
Outside the iron gates, in the darkest shadows of a nearby tree, stood a solitary female figure wrapped in a dark, heavy cloak. The wind moaned low and mournful. As the figure took a single step forward, the wind moved to greet her. A trail of dry leaves swirled in its wake as the breezes converged about the woman’s legs, caressing and touching with adoration and respect as a servant would its master. Leaves circled the woman, briefly riding the chill air before launching about in a chaotic pattern then once again falling to stillness against the cooling ground. <br>
<br>
The woman began to incant softly into the night, her gentle words of spoken power carried hauntingly along the currents of air, echoing tenderly moments after she herself had finished. With a quiet sucking noise, air was suddenly displaced by the appearance of a tiny fairy - her delicate silvery wings fanned effortlessly so that she maintained eye contact with her Mistress as they discussed matters most dark. <br>
<br>
After a few brief whispers from the fairy’s tinkling bell-like voice, the cloaked Lady replied in hushed tones, “I too have felt the coming Darkness. Its unnatural presence beckons so powerfully. I have felt its tendrils coil and snake outward through the Nektulos forest and brush the edge of my soul. It is a Darkness that can be seen so clearly from the corner of one’s eye, but missed so completely when seen from straight on.” <br>
<br>
The dark Lady incanted slowly into the night air and faded to shadow. She continued speaking hidden from view, her voice a distant echo, layer upon layer whispering in the wind, “You will continue your watch, my summons. Observe the night, observe High Castle and observe the Champions. All is not as it seems.” <br>
<br>
Her fading voice, nearly a whisper, continues on, “We will wait for this ‘Darkness.’ Its time is nearly upon us all. Indeed, astute little one, something wicked this way comes…”<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~eden444/images/talene_banner1.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/belvenelite.showUserPublicProfile?gid=candraverbena>Candra Verbena</A> at: 2/7/03 7:34:30 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#AB8C5B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/belvenelite.showUserPublicProfile?gid=candraverbena>Candra Verbena</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(2/7/03 7:14:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/felvenelitefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=94.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~eden444/images/candra_small.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Something Wicked This Way Comes</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>AUTHOR: Candra Verbena</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Tytalus Verbana appeared much the same as Candra remembered him; long haired, mustached, and possessed of innate charm. His swarthy complexion was highlighted by prominent cheekbones and a pair of green eyes that captivated all who met his gaze. His strong, aristocratic nose suggested his noble ancestry. <br>
<br>
Candra quietly marveled at his timeless good-looks. Indeed, the man looked remarkably ageless for a human. Then again, no one knew better than an enchantress that looks could be deceiving. She couldn’t help but pry a little, “You’re looking remarkably well, father.”<br>
<br>
“Shall I say ‘Thank you’ and pretend your interest is a compliment?”<br>
<br>
A light smirk played over Candra’s lips. Candra liked a challenge and there was no one more challenging than her father. He had always been little larger than life when she was a young girl. His presence filled any room he entered. <br>
<br>
As she journeyed to this meeting, Candra had thought that effect would be diminished by his greater years and the harsh times he’d endured. The looking glass related a vague figure, somewhat obscured, she believed, by magic meant to foul attempts to scry his whereabouts. She filled in the blanks herself and believed the wizard to be old, tired and broken, a fallen champion whose power was but a whisper of the bellow it used to be. Well, you know what they say about when one “assumes”, she thought.<br>
<br>
Candra showed the man a slight grin as she replied to his obviously rhetorical question, “You’ll do as you please. You always have.”<br>
<br>
“Where are my manners?” Tytatlus extended his hand to the levitating enchantress. His mustache lent the grin bending his lips a feral charm. “Come aboard, won’t you? I’m afraid the accommodations here may not be suiting to a lady of your refined tastes. My, err...yacht is out for repairs.” He shot her a wink and showed his white teeth.<br>
<br>
Candra accepted the invitation and took the man’s hand. Contrary to popular belief, she had spent many a day on a similar boat enjoying the very same sport. She found the relative peace of fishing a wonderful exercise of patience and meditation. Her movements proved that fact as she easily situated herself to settle into the boats meager comforts.<br>
<br>
If Tytalus noticed her confidence, he didn’t let it show. “So what brings you about after so many years, my dear? I would like to think the call is purely social, but I know you better than that.”<br>
<br>
Candra didn’t waste any time feigning hurt feelings or shock in the face of brutal honesty. She saw no reason for the soft and gentle approach, she wasn’t feeling much in the mood to play around anyway, “I need your help to unravel a mystery. One that I feel will become a threat to the Realm if allowed to go on unchecked.”<br>
<br>
Intrigued, Tytalus leaned forward towards her. “Please continue.”<br>
<br>
Candra did her best to relay the story of the young paladin, Yadien and then the dreams, or rather nightmares, which haunted her sleep. She told him of the auguries she’d cast and of the sense of dread that had made its home in her heart.<br>
<br>
Tytalus listened eagerly to all she had to say, enrapt by the telling. Candra could only guess at the thoughts that ran through his mind. She dared not steal them. It would be considered rude if she was caught in the act, then too her father’s sanity was rumored to be a fragile thing and she, as a rule, shied away from prying into the minds of the mad. <br>
<br>
The enchantress searched through the wild look in the wizard’s wondrous green eyes. They were full of questions that were already tripping over his tongue to be asked.<br>
<br>
Tytalus stammered, “Tell me about the elf Yadien. Did the clerics make any effort to recall his soul to his body?”<br>
<br>
Candra held on to his gaze. “Yes, but they could not call it back. Something about...”<br>
<br>
A look of dread washed over Tytalus’ face. He turned slightly, looking away. Candra couldn’t determine if he did for distraction or to hide the growing fear she read in his expression. “It swallows souls, Candra. Leaving nothing but the shell behind.”<br>
<br>
He looked her up and down as if sizing her up. “These nightmares you speak of....I’m curious. Did you touch Its mind, Candra?”<br>
<br>
It was a detail she’s not told anyone. His intense look compelled her to answer him with honesty. “Yes.”<br>
<br>
“And what did you see there?”<br>
<br>
She was trembling and could not stop herself from doing so as she called that memory to present thought. “I saw a creature comprised of darkness and death. It thrived for the power of the souls it had consumed and was bent on a singular mission.”<br>
<br>
“What mission, Candra? Tell me! I must know!”<br>
<br>
“It...It intends to murder the world.” For her brief contact with the dark force that had possessed Yadien, Candra had caught a glimpse at something powerful and unique. A force of destruction the likes of which she’d never thought possible. It had the presence of a god, but lacked the power. She considered Its potential and ambition and couldn’t help but wonder -“What is 'It', father?”<br>
<br>
“I cannot say.”<br>
<br>
“Cannot or will not?” she demanded<br>
<br>
Tytalus turned on his daughter with wild, wide eyes, his voice charged with restrained power. “CANNOT!” The boat swayed violently, rocked by the churning waters that floated it.<br>
<br>
Candra felt dizzy, taken aback by the magic that emanated from the wizard. She found herself suffocating in the presence of such a phenomenon. She struggled against it, gripping the boat’s rim to steady herself. She looked back at her father with a pleading look.<br>
<br>
Tytalus caught her look and took control of his self. An apology shaped his expression as he reigned in the magic that had, for a moment, gotten away from him.<br>
<br>
Candra said nothing. She simply looked at the man across from her. Tytalus sat there, hugging himself. He seemed so vulnerable, but the display of power he’d shown warned Candra towards caution. A part of her longed to go to Tytalus and comfort him, but she was altogether too afraid; of his power, of losing time.<br>
<br>
Her lips parted to loose a voice so soft it fell over her father’s senses like the touch of feathers. A gentle breeze washed over the man, clearing his mind, sharpening his focus. “Please father, help me.”<br>
<br>
Tytalus seemed transformed as he looked back at Candra. There was a clear look in his eyes and his voice carried the same trait. ”It was centuries ago, m’dear, during a time that has come to be known as the Lost Age. The orcs had not yet settled into Greater Faydark and the outpost Firiona Vie was not even conceived in thought.<br>
<br>
&quot;The progenitors of the Immaculate Order of Dragons had not yet finished constructing their keep when a powerful threat...a danger unlike any they had known came upon the Realm and made fast plans to murder it. The Order gathered its allies and journeyed en masse in search of a beast that could leap from form to form. After countless lives had been lost It was still at large; pursuing an agenda that confounded all who ran after It. It was an event that the guild’s historians dubbed ‘The Great Contagion” for It swept over the land like a plague. In the end the Order and its allies prevailed against its foe, but they lacked a means to destroy its life. It is said that a great circle of powerful spell casters from each of the guilds gathered to cast a work of will that bound the beast in the empty void of space and time, thus bringing that awful chapter of history to a close.”<br>
<br>
Candra seemed confused, “How is it that I’ve never heard this before?”<br>
<br>
“There is a reason why they call it the Lost Age, Candra.”<br>
<br>
She nodded and to her credit didn’t blush for the embarrassment she felt. “Tell me more.”<br>
<br>
“You’ve heard all that I remember.”<br>
<br>
“It’s not enough, father. I need to know it’s name, its purpose and how, if all you’ve said is true, it escaped its prison.”<br>
<br>
Tytalus grinned. It was obvious the wizard was impressed by his daughter’s drive. He nodded. “There is one who can provide the information you seek.”<br>
<br>
Candra’s violet eyes blazed with curiosity. “Tell me!”<br>
<br>
Tytalus’ green eyes leveled to that determined gaze as he submitted to his daughter’s demand. He uttered only one word in reply. “Wuoshi.”<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~eden444/images/The%20Mind's%20Eye"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/belvenelite.showUserPublicProfile?gid=candraverbena>Candra Verbena</A> at: 2/7/03 8:56:53 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#BA9F70><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/belvenelite.showUserPublicProfile?gid=candraverbena>Candra Verbena</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 22<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(2/7/03 7:16:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/felvenelitefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=94.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~eden444/images/candra_small.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Something Wicked This Way Comes</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>AUTHOR: Talene Vhaerun</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The air was heavy with shadow and damp with moisture as it made its way from the dark, misting night into the sheltered underground of the Neriak, the Tier’dal city fortress. It seemed to breathe a sigh of relief to those that listened as it once again swept through the familiar halls lit by sigils and runes that cast a welcoming, comfortable glow. The breeze blew slowly through the bustling Foreign Quarter, making its invisible presence felt more than known. Its chill raised the course hairs on an Ogre Blacksmith’s sweaty arm and drew a slight gasp from the lips of a surprised human serving wench as its willowy touch lightly brushed her cheek. <br>
<br>
The meandering current continued its progress deeper into the vast underground city, past the dark, shadow-weaved adamantine gates securing the Neriak Commons from the outsiders taking residence in the Foreign Quarter. It swirled between the legs of patrolling guards and ever alert sentries. To those Tier’dal born with a heightened magical affinity, the air appeared to glimmer and sparkle briefly as it released yet another weary sigh, trembling as the dark magic of the Neriak embraced it. The air took one last pause, becoming a gently whirling dervish. It warmed its smoke-like tendrils against the glowing embers of the unused Tier’dal forge before it moved towards the third and final gate of the Neriak. <br>
<br>
The air met no welcome as it moved to and past the third gate. No cheery greeting. No affectionate acknowledgement. It was but a servant to its Mistress, the Witch of the Nektulos. It moved low across the rough hewn stone passages bringing a stir of dust and mites that marked its invisible passage. It rose from the ground and floated upward as it crossed a walkway over a watery pool to avoid picking up the chill from the nearby liquid. The tiny breeze reached the edge of a darkened structure set in the furthest recesses of the Neriak caverns. It approached an open window on the second floor and paused as another of its kind slowly drifted out. The breezes mingled, sharing touch, current and warmth if but for only a passing moment. The caresses ended far too quickly and the breezes split into their own strands, flowing to complete their missions. <br>
<br>
The breeze lazily entered the dimly lit room and found its Mistress sitting perfectly ridged, awaiting its arrival and news. Even though her face was wrapped in shadow and darkness, her pale blue eyes pierced the gloom as the play of sigil magic light flickered across her features. Her darkly painted lips parted ever so slowly as she raised one hand before her, “Welcome, Jenikabob.” <br>
<br>
The elemental wind paused as Talene uttered its true name. It moved low to the ground as if kneeling before her and waited a moment before rising and wrapping itself about her arm. Its borrowed warmth flushed her smooth skin, bringing a smile to those same lips that were frigid with formality a moment earlier. Talene moved her second hand about the wind, cradling it in her lap as if it were a small pet. The wind, eager to please its Mistress, began its tale with news from the Karanas, breathing but one word, “Wuoshi.”<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~eden444/images/talene_banner1.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/belvenelite.showUserPublicProfile?gid=candraverbena>Candra Verbena</A> at: 2/7/03 7:35:13 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#AB8C5B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/belvenelite.showUserPublicProfile?gid=candraverbena>Candra Verbena</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(2/7/03 7:18:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/felvenelitefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=94.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~eden444/images/candra_small.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Something Wicked This Way Comes</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>AUTHOR: Candra Verbena</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
A rush of warm air breathed over Candra’s body as she appeared in Wakening Land. It was a welcome sensation after leaving the harsh cold of the Great Divide. She slowly stepped away from the portal, moving towards the center of the druid circle. The druid Halai had arrived moments before her and stood patiently, waiting.<br>
<br>
Candra met up with the elf, offering him a smile as warm as their environs. “Thank you, Halai. You’ve been so helpful, considering...”<br>
<br>
“Considering that what you intend to do is madness!” There was no apology to follow for his snapping remark. From the moment the enchantress explained her reasons for seeking him out, Halai had done his best to talk her out it.<br>
<br>
Decided in her course of action, Candra would not be swayed to change. She ignored his warning. The anxiety that gripped her stomach was already great and no good could come from further exposure to discouraging words.<br>
<br>
She took a moment to shrug off the furs that wrapped her shapely figure to reveal a form flattering tunic and matching leggings. With Coldain skin boots and gloves, she was a study of warm tones, browns and golds. Her dark hair was gathered into a thick braid that fell just shy of the center of her back.<br>
<br>
Her violet gaze swept over the area as she considered The Wakening Land. It was a large forested valley on an otherwise frozen continent. The goddess Tunare had a very palpable presence, and was likely the reason that the area was so full of life. Candra moved away from the ring’s center, stepping towards the egress.<br>
<br>
Halai followed after her, his mouth still moving. As he had yet to say anything that would encourage her, Candra was still ignoring him. She suddenly felt his gentle grip on her bicep, tugging her towards him. She turned to face her guildsman with a curious look drawn over her features.<br>
<br>
“I have faith in you, M’Lady.” His words rang with a sincerity that was echoed by his expression. His eyes held such concern. “Do not think for one moment that I do not. That which you seek is a powerful force and I only mean to urge you towards caution. It is madness for you to go alone.”<br>
<br>
“Trust in that faith, my friend. I do what must be done. This is the only way.”<br>
<br>
The druid seemed unconvinced, but was all talked out. He gave Candra a slow nod and took a step back as assent. “I shall wait for you here then, Regentia. May the Great Mother see you through this and return you safely to me soon.”<br>
<br>
She shared a reassuring smile with Halai, then turned away to leave the circle.<br>
<br>
Away from the Dragon Portal, Candra expected to be greeted with dramatic silence. She imagined an ominous, deep quiet to guide her path. The reality was that the moment she crossed over the circle’s threshold her senses were assaulted by signs of a great battle nearby. <br>
<br>
The smells of blood and magic rode the warm wind. Clashing weapons and cries of anguish rang in her ears. Her mind was reeling from fear and surprise. She turned about, spinning and searching for the source of such bedlam.<br>
<br>
Her eyes landed on a sight that was as amazing as it was terrible. Either, a group of adventurers had made the mistake of entering The Wakening Land unaware of the great dragon that made its home there, or they had come to seek it out with the intention of slaying the great beast for the fame and wealth that such a kill would bring them.<br>
<br>
Candra’s heart sank as she glanced over the mangled bodies that littered the ground; streams of crimson connecting them. She turned to those still standing and ached for the imminent loss of life. There were three of them. Candra studied each and guessed them to be a human cleric, and a Feir’Dal druid and ranger. There was nothing she could do to help them as she was unwilling to compromise her standing with the flight of dragons that made up the sect known as the Claws of Veeshan. Any attempt to help these poor souls would certainly earn the dragon’s enmity and deliver her into Death’s embrace.<br>
<br>
A splatter of blood and bits of gore had ruined the golden armor of the group’s remaining cleric; most of it not his own. The human struggled with a prayer for healing, but was cut short by a talon through his breast. The ranger fell soon after, burned to cinders as she tried to save her human companion. The druid was quick to think and took advantage of the moment to cast a spell that would take him away from the carnage. The very air about him rippled as he opened a rift in space-time, but alas, his gate proved unstable. His magic faltered and a powerful sweep of the dragon’s claws put an end to any notion of a second attempt.<br>
<br>
The dragon raised its long neck and roared so fiercely that the world shook. Candra fell to her knees, trembling for reasons besides the shaking ground beneath her feet. She struggled to compose herself, making a great effort to stand. When she had accomplished that feat, the enchantress looked up to find the dragon’s blazing serpentine gaze upon her.<br>
<br>
In that moment of incredible awe, the dragon slowly approaching - all rational thought fled her screaming mind. <br>
<br>
